metadata.name: Kinetic Bug #179
metadata.description:
Best viewed on a decent GPU,  because physics simulations are performance intensive. Otherwise you might encounter a bug...

In a world of digital data, a new life is born. We are not alone...
Explore how kinetic bugs make their way through the world. What will their destiny be?
It's curious that we can sympathize to a predefined creature living it's predestined life in the digital world. Coding in the computer abyss reveals interesting worlds.

Keyboard
[ space ] - jump
[ click ] - increase velocity briefly
[ r ] - restart simulation
[ s ] - save image
[ f ] - full screen

Mobile
[ two finger tap ] - jump
[ tap ] - increase velocity briefly

Created with Three.js + rapier.js
Copyright (c) July 2022 Shaderism

metadata.name: Reverberations #64
metadata.description:
[ CLICK TO START THE SOUND ]
Best viewed on a decent GPU for 60fps rendering
Play the instrument by clicking or touching the blobs
Supports any aspect ratio, however the resulting simulation will vary!

Everything in the universe is made up of vibrating energy, including us. Our thoughts and emotions are also vibrations of energy that influence the frequencies around us. 
Be kind.

Controls
[ click / touch ] - split blobs
[ /?play ] - query string to avoid automatic splits

metadata.name: Sixty# #57
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe there’s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press ’s’ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Wondering #217
metadata.description:
The work contains a fluid simulation. I put random forces into the simulation and let it run 500 steps to create a flow field and then use it to generate the visuals. 

I choose fluid simulation instead of curl noise or any other noise function because I believe the fluid simulation could generate a movement that's more dynamic and organic. The result is a combination of big and small vortices.


This piece requires WebGL2 to run, please check and make sure this runs on your device in advance. Also you can press the spacebar to toggle the camera control.
